org.apache.drill.exec.physical.impl.scan.project

Class TestNullColumnLoader

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.apache.drill.test.BaseTest
      • org.apache.drill.test.DrillTest
        • org.apache.drill.test.SubOperatorTest
          • org.apache.drill.exec.physical.impl.scan.project.TestNullColumnLoader

  • public class TestNullColumnLoader
extends SubOperatorTest
    Test the mechanism that handles all-null columns during projection. An all-null column is one projected in the query, but which does not actually exist in the underlying data source (or input operator.)

    In anticipation of having type information, this mechanism can create the classic nullable Int null column, or one of any other type and mode.

    • Method Detail

      • testBasics

        public void testBasics()
        Test the simplest case: default null type, nothing in the vector cache. Specify no column type, the special NULL type, or a predefined type. Output types should be set accordingly.

      • testCustomNullType

        public void testCustomNullType()
        Test the ability to use a type other than nullable INT for null columns. This occurs, for example, in the CSV reader where no column is ever INT (nullable or otherwise) and we want our null columns to be (non-nullable) VARCHAR.

      • testDefaultValue

        public void testDefaultValue()
        Test the ability to provide a default value for a "null" column. Default values are only allowed for required "null" columns. For nullable columns, NULL is already the default.

      • testCachedTypesMapToNullable

        public void testCachedTypesMapToNullable()
        Drill requires "schema persistence": if a scan operator reads two files, F1 and F2, then the scan operator must provide the same vectors from both readers. Not just the same types, the same value vector instances (but, of course, populated with different data.)

        Test the case in which the reader for F1 found columns (a, b, c) but, F2 found only (a, b), requiring that we fill in column c, filled with nulls, but of the same type that it was in file F1. We use a vector cache to pull off this trick. This test ensures that the null column mechanism looks in that vector cache when asked to create a nullable column.

      • testCachedTypesAllowRequired

        public void testCachedTypesAllowRequired()
        Suppose, in the previous test, that one of the columns that goes missing is a required column. The null-column mechanism can create the "null" column as a required column, then fill it with empty values (zero or "") -- if the scan operator feels doing so would be helpful.

      • testNullColumnBuilder

        public void testNullColumnBuilder()
        Test the shim class that adapts between the null column loader and the projection mechanism. The projection mechanism uses this to pull in the null columns which the null column loader has created.

      • testNullColumnBuilderWithSchema

        public void testNullColumnBuilderWithSchema()
        Test using an output schema, along with a default value property, to define a default value for missing columns.

      • testSchemaWithConflicts

        public void testSchemaWithConflicts()
        Test the various conflicts that can occur:
        • Schema is required, but no default value for null column.
        • Query wants a different type than that in the schema.
        • Query wants a different mode than that in the schema.
            • The type and mode provided to the builder is that which would result from schema smoothing. The types and modes should usually match, but verify the rules when they don't.

            Defaults for null columns are ignored: null columns use NULL as the null value.
